<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="188" pageId="15" pageNumber="186" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="15.[163,1070,1364,1562]" pageId="15" pageNumber="186">
C o m m e n t: The original description of this conspicuous species is based on two females from 
<collectingCountry box="[305,365,1393,1415]" name="Nepal" pageId="15" pageNumber="186">Nepal</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="ASSING V" box="[381,532,1393,1415]" pageId="15" pageNumber="186" pagination="115 - 190" refId="ref11068" refString="ASSING V. (2012 a): The Rugilus species of the Palaearctic and Oriental regions (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Stuttgarter Beitrage zur Naturkunde A, Neue Serie 5: 115 - 190." type="journal article" year="2012">ASSING 2012a</bibRefCitation>
). The above first record from 
<collectingCountry box="[843,892,1394,1415]" name="Laos" pageId="15" pageNumber="186">Laos</collectingCountry>
suggests that the species is widespread in the East Palaearctic and Oriental regions (Map 4). The subgeneric affiliations are still unclarified, but its hypothesized close relationship to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rugilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="186" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saudicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="186">R. saudicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see the following section) suggests that both species may have their closest relatives in the Afrotropical region. The previously unknown male sexual characters are as follows:
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4507339" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4507339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4507339/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="187" startId="16.[163,203,1425,1445]" targetBox="[168,1061,201,1403]" targetPageId="16">
<paragraph blockId="16.[163,1071,1424,1514]" pageId="16" pageNumber="187">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[163,263,1425,1445]" pageId="16" pageNumber="187">Figs 23-30</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="ASSING" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2012" box="[275,486,1424,1445]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rugilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lucens">
<emphasis box="[275,409,1424,1445]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="187">Rugilus lucens</emphasis>
ASSING
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[500,554,1425,1445]" pageId="16" pageNumber="187">23-25</emphasis>
) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Assing, 2013" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2013" box="[608,714,1424,1446]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rugilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saudicus" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis box="[608,714,1424,1446]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="187">R. saudicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[719,786,1425,1445]" pageId="16" pageNumber="187" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[799,853,1425,1445]" pageId="16" pageNumber="187">26-30</emphasis>
): (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[880,938,1425,1445]" pageId="16" pageNumber="187">23, 27</emphasis>
) male sternite VIII; (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[225,286,1448,1468]" pageId="16" pageNumber="187">24, 28</emphasis>
) aedeagus in lateral view; (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[556,618,1448,1468]" pageId="16" pageNumber="187">25, 29</emphasis>
) aedeagus in ventral view; (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[894,917,1448,1468]" pageId="16" pageNumber="187">26</emphasis>
) forebody; (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1040,1063,1448,1468]" pageId="16" pageNumber="187">30</emphasis>
) apical portion of aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 26: 1.0 mm; 23, 27: 0.2 mm; 24-25, 28-30: 0.1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="17.[163,1071,203,284]" pageId="17" pageNumber="188">
3: sternite VII transverse and with broadly concave posterior margin; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs 23-30" captionStartId="16.[163,203,1425,1445]" captionTargetBox="[168,1061,201,1403]" captionTargetId="figure-92@16.[163,1070,197,1407]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figs 23-30: Rugilus lucens ASSING (23-25) and R. saudicus nov.sp. (26-30): (23, 27) male sternite VIII; (24, 28) aedeagus in lateral view; (25, 29) aedeagus in ventral view; (26) forebody; (30) apical portion of aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 26: 1.0 mm; 23, 27: 0.2 mm; 24-25, 28-30: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4507339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4507339/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="188">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
) with dense pubescence, posteriorly with broad and shallow excision; aedeagus (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs 23-30" captionStartId="16.[163,203,1425,1445]" captionTargetBox="[168,1061,201,1403]" captionTargetId="figure-92@16.[163,1070,197,1407]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figs 23-30: Rugilus lucens ASSING (23-25) and R. saudicus nov.sp. (26-30): (23, 27) male sternite VIII; (24, 28) aedeagus in lateral view; (25, 29) aedeagus in ventral view; (26) forebody; (30) apical portion of aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 26: 1.0 mm; 23, 27: 0.2 mm; 24-25, 28-30: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4507339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4507339/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="188">Figs 24-25</figureCitation>
